Backend architecture:

The backend is built with FastAPI and organized into clear modules:

- cv: CV parsing, deterministic skill extraction, project extraction
- job_description: Mistral-based job-description extraction and saved job profile catalog
- matching: skill normalization, alias matching, broad skill matching, weighted scoring
- interview: preparation mode, adaptive interview mode, code runner, answer scoring, RAG grounding
- app: authentication, user/session management, API routes, settings, and admin tools

Frontend architecture:

The current primary UI is built in React.

It includes:

- job skill extraction
- CV vs saved role matching
- CV vs new job-description matching
- interview preparation mode
- adaptive interview mode
- progress dashboards
- admin settings
- user and admin management
- RAG learning visualization
- job-description evaluation dataset builder
- downloadable question sets, match outputs, and interview reports

I kept the older Streamlit prototype separately for reference, while React is now the main application UI.

Transparency and explainability:

I wanted the system to be transparent from both the user and admin perspective.

For users:

- They can see exactly which CV skills matched the role requirements
- They can see exactly which required skills are missing
- They can see whether the gap is in strongly required skills, required skills, tools/platforms, preferred skills, or soft skills
- They can inspect category-wise score contribution rather than only seeing one final percentage

For admins:

- Skill weights can be configured through the UI
- Skill aliases can be updated through the UI
- Broad skill mappings can be updated through the UI
- Evaluation datasets can be created through the UI
- Scoring behavior becomes easier to audit and improve over time

